description:
In PyMongo's restructured text documentation, replace method signatures like these:
{code}
find([filter=None[, projection=None[, skip=0[, limit=0[, no_cursor_timeout=False[, cursor_type=NON_TAILABLE[, sort=None[, allow_partial_results=False[, oplog_replay=False[, modifiers=None[, manipulate=True]]]]]]]]]]])
{code}
...with normal signatures:
{code}
find(filter=None, projection=None, skip=0, limit=0, no_cursor_timeout=False, cursor_type=NON_TAILABLE, sort=None, allow_partial_results=False, oplog_replay=False, modifiers=None, manipulate=True)
{code}

There one huge behaviour change in PyMongo 3, which is not documented if at all wished, but in my opinion is a bug (and therefore this ticket).

In collection.py, in the save() method, we had in PyMongo 2.X:

{noformat}
self.update({"_id": to_save["_id"]}, to_save, True, manipulate, safe, check_keys=check_keys, **kwargs)
        return to_save.get("_id", None)
{noformat}

And now in PyMongo 3.0:

{noformat}
self._update(sock_info, {"_id": to_save["_id"]}, to_save, True, check_keys, False, manipulate, write_concern)
{noformat}

With no return !!! Whereas many apps base on the fact to check for the id to now if the upsert really worked.

fails to "InvalidDocument: Cannot encode object: <core.db.submodels.BoundService object at 0x000000000361B940>"
when i'am try to update with 
{code}
db[collection].update({'_id': id}, {'$set': {'services': {u'9e0b161ee51811e4adf33c970e3da6e8': service}}})
{code}
Although a make SONManipulator and add it to db by db.add_son_manipulator. It's work fine, because when i retieve data from db i get it serialized to instance of BoundService class.

This is a really strange one...

When connecting through a mongos, I'm seeing an issue where find_one with PRIMARY_PREFERRED doesn't return any output.

{code}
c = ...some_collection ...
c.with_options(read_preference=ReadPreference.PRIMARY_PREFERRED)
c.find_one({'symbol': symbol}, sort=[('version', pymongo.DESCENDING)])
{code}

returns {{None}}. Whereas:

{code}
c.find_one({'symbol': symbol})
{code}

return an item.

{code}
len(list(c.find({'symbol': symbol}))
Out[76]: 25

In [79]: [x for x in list(c.find({'symbol': symbol})) if x is None]
Out[79]: []
{code}

Note a normal {{find}} finds nothing too.
{code}
In [84]: c = lib._versions.with_options(read_preference=ReadPreference.PRIMARY_PREFERRED)
In [85]: len(list(c.find({'symbol': symbol}, sort=[('version', pymongo.DESCENDING)])))
Out[85]: 0
{code}


If I change the read-preference, it works!

{code}
In [82]: c = lib._versions.with_options(read_preference=ReadPreference.PRIMARY)
In [83]: len(list(c.find({'symbol': symbol}, sort=[('version', pymongo.DESCENDING)])))
Out[83]: 25
{code}
